You nailed it, Nathan â€” your controller is clean, but yeahâ€¦ the @ApiResponses section is getting a bit "cluttercore" ğŸ˜… Especially with so many endpoints. Letâ€™s declutter it while keeping full OpenAPI support â€” the professional way. Here's what we can do:

âœ… Option 1: Move Swagger Annotations to a Common Interface (Interface-Driven API Docs)
Create a TaskControllerDocs.  interface:

public interface TaskControllerDocs {

    @Operation(summary = "Create a Task")
    @ApiResponses({
            @ApiResponse(responseCode = "201", description = "Task created successfully"),
            @ApiResponse(responseCode = "400", description = "Validation error"),
            @ApiResponse(responseCode = "500", description = "Internal server error")
    })
    @PostMapping("/taskDto")
    Object createTask(@RequestBody Object taskDto);


    @Operation(summary = "Get all Tasks")
    @ApiResponses({
            @ApiResponse(responseCode = "200", description = "Fetched all tasks successfully"),
            @ApiResponse(responseCode = "500", description = "Internal server error")
    })
    @GetMapping("/tasks")
    Object getAllTask();

    // Add rest of the methods similarly...
}
Now your actual controller will just implement that interface:




@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api")
@Slf4j
@Tag(name = "Task Management V2", description = "APIs for managing tasks")
public class TaskController implements TaskControllerDocs {
    // No more clunky annotations here!
}
âœ¨ Result?
âœ… Cleaner controller

âœ… Full Swagger/OpenAPI support

âœ… Centralized documentation for easy  ing or reuse

âœ… Option 2: Use @ApiResponse at method level only for exceptions
If interface-based feels too formal for now, try only annotating the most meaningful or differing responses. E.g.:




@Operation(summary = "Create a Task")
@PostMapping("/taskDto")
public ResponseEntity<Optional<TaskDto>> createTask(@RequestBody @Valid TaskDto taskDto) {
    return new ResponseEntity<>(taskService.createTask(taskDto), HttpStatus.CREATED);
}
ğŸ’¡ Swagger will auto-generate 200/201 based on the @PostMapping or @PutMapping if you skip @ApiResponses.

âœ… Option 3: Use @ApiResponse group-level at class level (less preferred)
Not super common, but you can define a reusable @ApiResponses block if your responses are mostly the same.




@ApiResponses({
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "500", description = "Internal server error"),
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "400", description = "Validation error")
})
@RestController
public class TaskController {
    ...
}
ğŸ”¸ Downside: not specific per endpoint.

ğŸ§  Best Practice Recommendation (my 2 cents):
Scenario	Best Pick
Big team / Reuse / Docs in control	âœ… Interface-driven (TaskControllerDocs)
Small project / Clean but flexible	âœ… Use only @Operation or one or two key @ApiResponses
Super minimalist dev	Skip @ApiResponses entirely â€” let OpenAPI infer based on @ResponseStatus / HttpStatus in controller

