ChatGPT said:
Superb question mama! ğŸ¤
You're absolutely right to ask â€” we handled all the error response codes globally using class-level @ApiResponses, but what about the successful ones like 200, 201, 202? ğŸŸ¢

ğŸ§  Here's the golden rule in Swagger/OpenAPI:
âœ… Success responses (200, 201, 202, etc.) should be specified at the method level.
âŒ Do not put them at class level â€” because they differ per endpoint (GET vs POST vs PUT).

ğŸ” Why?
Method Type	Typical Success Code
GET	200 OK
POST	201 Created
PUT/PATCH	202 Accepted
DELETE	202 Accepted or 204 No Content

So, trying to group these at class level wouldn't be meaningful â€” it may confuse the Swagger doc and lead to incorrect API behavior representation.

âœ… What You Should Do:
Keep your class-level responses for common failures:




@ApiResponses({
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "400", description = "Bad Request / Validation error"),
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "404", description = "Resource not found"),
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "500", description = "Internal Server Error")
})
Then just add 1 success response per method, depending on its purpose:

ğŸ”§ Example:



@Operation(summary = "Create a Task")
@ApiResponse(responseCode = "201", description = "Task created successfully")
@PostMapping("/taskDto")
public ResponseEntity<Optional<TaskDto>> createTask(@RequestBody @Valid TaskDto taskDto) {
    return new ResponseEntity<>(taskService.createTask(taskDto), HttpStatus.CREATED);
}



@Operation(summary = "Get all Tasks")
@ApiResponse(responseCode = "200", description = "Fetched all tasks successfully")
@GetMapping("/tasks")
public ResponseEntity<List<TaskDto>> getAllTask() {
    return ResponseEntity.ok(taskService.getAllTask());
}



@Operation(summary = "Update a Task")
@ApiResponse(responseCode = "202", description = "Task updated successfully")
@PutMapping("/task/")
public ResponseEntity<Optional<TaskDto>> updateTask(@RequestBody @Valid TaskDto taskDto) {
    return new ResponseEntity<>(taskService.updateTask(taskDto), HttpStatus.ACCEPTED);
}
âœ¨ Final Verdict:
Type	Where to put it?	Why?
Success codes	âœ… Method-level	Varies based on operation type
Error codes	âœ… Class-level (global)	Same for most/all endpoints

Why in swager for every response schema is coming. i dont want

ChatGPT said:
Great catch ra Nathan ğŸ‘€ â€” what you're seeing in the Swagger UI is OpenAPI auto-generating response schemas for every response code (like 200, 400, 404 etc.) based on your controllerâ€™s return type (ResponseEntity<TaskDto> or Optional<TaskDto>).

Thatâ€™s why itâ€™s showing the same schema (i.e., TaskDto) even for error responses â€” which is not correct and also clutters the UI ğŸ’¥.

ğŸ§¨ Problem:
Springdoc/OpenAPI is assuming all response codes return the same model (TaskDto) â€” unless you explicitly tell it otherwise.

âœ… Solution: Use @ApiResponse(..., content = @Content(...)) and set content = @Content() for error responses
By setting content = @Content() explicitly, you tell Swagger:

âŒ Don't attach any schema to this response.
ğŸ§¼ Just describe it â€” donâ€™t generate dummy example JSON.

ğŸ”§ Example Fix:
Instead of this (which causes schema generation for 400/404):




@ApiResponse(responseCode = "400", description = "Bad Request / Validation error")
@ApiResponse(responseCode = "404", description = "Resource not found")
Do this ğŸ‘‡ (clean, no schema block shown):




@ApiResponse(responseCode = "400", description = "Bad Request / Validation error", content = @Content)
@ApiResponse(responseCode = "404", description = "Resource not found", content = @Content)
You can apply this at both method or class level.

âœ… Final @ApiResponses at class level (your case)



@ApiResponses({
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "400", description = "Bad Request / Validation error", content = @Content),
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "404", description = "Resource not found", content = @Content),
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "500", description = "Internal Server Error", content = @Content)
})
Now your Swagger UI will show the code and description only, without dumping the schema block.

ğŸ§ª Bonus Tip:
If you're using a custom error class (like ErrorResponse), you can show it only for 400, and leave 404/500 clean:




@ApiResponse(responseCode = "400", description = "Validation error",
             content = @Content(mediaType = "application/json", schema = @Schema(implementation = ErrorResponse.class)))
ğŸ§¼ TL;DR:
You want...	Use this
No schema shown in Swagger	@ApiResponse(..., content = @Content)
Custom error model shown only	Use schema = @Schema(implementation = MyError.class)
Full cleanup (your case)	âœ… Do this at class level for all 400/404/500 codes


